<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a markdown table?", answer: "A markdown table is a way to represent tabular data using plain text characters. It uses pipe characters (|) to separate columns and hyphens (-) to create a separator row between the header and data rows. Markdown tables are widely supported in GitHub, GitLab, Reddit, Stack Overflow, Notion, and most documentation platforms. They render as formatted HTML tables when the markdown is processed." },
  { question: "How do I create a markdown table manually?", answer: "Start with the header row, separating each column with a pipe character (|). On the next line, add a separator row with hyphens between pipes to divide the header from the data. Then add data rows using the same pipe-separated format. For example: '| Name | Age |' on line 1, '| --- | --- |' on line 2, and '| Alice | 30 |' on line 3. Leading and trailing pipes are optional in some parsers but recommended for clarity." },
  { question: "Can I align columns in a markdown table?", answer: "Yes. The separator row supports alignment indicators using colons. A colon on the left (|:---|) produces left-aligned text, a colon on the right (|---:|) produces right-aligned text, and colons on both sides (|:---:|) produces centered text. No colons (|---|) defaults to left alignment. Not all markdown renderers support alignment, but GitHub, GitLab, and most modern platforms do." },
  { question: "Can I paste data from a spreadsheet into the table?", answer: "Yes. This tool supports pasting tab-separated data from spreadsheets like Excel and Google Sheets. When you copy cells from a spreadsheet, they are placed on the clipboard as tab-separated text. Click on the cell where you want the pasted data to begin and paste normally. The tool detects the tab characters and distributes the values across the corresponding cells in the grid." },
  { question: "What are the limitations of markdown tables?", answer: "Markdown tables only support simple tabular data. They do not support merged cells (colspan or rowspan), nested tables, multi-line content within a single cell, or complex formatting like background colors. For these features, you need raw HTML tables. Markdown tables also require a header row; there is no standard way to create a headerless table in markdown. The pipe characters inside cell values must be escaped with a backslash." }
]) %>

